02:30.680 --> 02:33.592
I used to think a wedding
was a simple affair.

02:33.720 --> 02:36.712
Boy and girl meet.
They fall in love. He buys a ring.

02:36.840 --> 02:39.308
She buys a dress.
They say, "l do."

02:41.800 --> 02:44.997
I was wrong.
That's getting married.

02:45.120 --> 02:49.079
A wedding is an entirely
different proposition.

02:49.200 --> 02:52.237
I know.
I've just been through one.

02:52.360 --> 02:54.669
Not my own,
my daughter's--

02:54.800 --> 02:57.951
Annie Banks-MacKenzie.

02:58.080 --> 03:01.231
That's her married name--
MacKenzie.

03:03.160 --> 03:05.628
I'll be honest with you.

03:05.760 --> 03:09.639
When I bought this house 17 years ago,
it cost less than this blessed event...

03:09.760 --> 03:13.275
in which Annie Banks
became Annie Banks-MacKenzie.

03:13.400 --> 03:15.789
I'm told that one day
I'll look back on all this...

03:15.920 --> 03:19.356
with great affection
and nostalgia.

03:19.480 --> 03:22.517
I hope so.

03:22.640 --> 03:24.835
You fathers will understand.

03:24.960 --> 03:27.793
You have a little girl...

03:27.920 --> 03:30.639
an adorable little girl
who looks up to you...

03:30.760 --> 03:34.355
and adores you in a way
you could never have imagined.

03:34.480 --> 03:39.600
I remember how her little hand
used to fit inside mine...

03:39.720 --> 03:43.235
how she used to lover to sit on my lap
and lean her head against my chest.

03:43.360 --> 03:46.238
She said I was her hero.

03:46.360 --> 03:48.271
Then the day comes when she wants
to get her ears pierced...

03:48.400 --> 03:51.437
and wants you to drop her off a block
before the movie theatre.

03:51.560 --> 03:54.597
Next thing you know, she's
wearing eye shadow and high heels.

03:54.720 --> 03:58.156
From that moment on
you're in a constant state of panic.

03:58.280 --> 04:00.874
You worry about her going out
with the wrong kind of guys...

04:01.000 --> 04:03.560
the kind of guys
who only want one thing.

04:03.680 --> 04:05.557
And you know exactly
what that one thing is...

04:05.680 --> 04:07.910
because it's the same thing you wanted
when you were their age.

04:09.640 --> 04:11.517
Then she gets a little older...

04:11.640 --> 04:14.473
and you quit worrying about her
meeting the wrong guy...

04:14.600 --> 04:17.319
and you worry about her
meeting the right guy.

04:17.440 --> 04:21.194
And that's the biggest fear
of all because...

04:22.440 --> 04:25.079
then you lose her.

04:25.200 --> 04:28.510
And before you know it, you're sitting
all alone in a big, empty house...

04:28.640 --> 04:33.475
wearing rice on your tux,
wondering what happened to your life.

04:33.600 --> 04:37.115
It was just six months ago
that it happened here.

04:37.240 --> 04:41.199
Just six months ago
that the storm broke.

04:43.760 --> 04:45.637
Annie had been studying
for her masters in architecture...

04:45.760 --> 04:47.671
for the past semester in Rome.

04:47.800 --> 04:50.155
I remember I was at work,
walking through the factory.

04:50.280 --> 04:54.068
I own a company called Sidekicks.
We manufacture athletic shoes.

04:54.200 --> 04:56.873
Anyway, I remember
how preoccupied I was that day.

04:57.000 --> 04:59.355
- I'm sorry, Mr Banks.
- My fault, Grace.

04:59.480 --> 05:03.758
Annie had never been that far away from
home, and she was due back any minute.

05:03.880 --> 05:06.314
I couldn't wait
to see the kid.

05:09.040 --> 05:12.191
George, she landed.

05:12.320 --> 05:14.788
My daughter has been studying abroad,
been flying for 11 hours.

05:14.920 --> 05:17.434
I'm not wild about her being
in the air. You have kids, Juan.

05:17.560 --> 05:20.199
You understand. It's-lt's better
when they're on the ground.

05:24.120 --> 05:26.190
I've always been
a concerned parent.

05:26.320 --> 05:29.517
I'm big on car seats,
seat belts, bedtimes, curfews...

05:29.640 --> 05:32.552
calling when you get somewhere,
never running with a sharp object.

05:32.680 --> 05:34.796
- Hi, George.
- What can I say? I'm a father.

05:34.920 --> 05:38.037
- Worrying comes with the territory.
- Is Nina picking her up at the airport?

05:38.160 --> 05:39.229
- Yeah.
- And you're gonna meet them?

05:39.360 --> 05:40.952
Yeah. Yeah,
I'm going home right now.

05:41.080 --> 05:42.911
I, uh-- My keys are--

05:43.040 --> 05:44.029
- Here.
- Oh, yeah. Sorry.

05:44.160 --> 05:46.037
- And sign this.
- Okay.

05:49.360 --> 05:51.590
- Hat.
- Okay, thanks. Now-- Oh!

05:54.240 --> 05:55.514
- Okay. Bye.
- Bring her by.

05:57.000 --> 06:00.276
I left work early because I had
a little something to pick up
for Annie's homecoming.

06:02.800 --> 06:07.157
We live in a small town in
Southern California called San Marino.

06:07.280 --> 06:09.555
I love this town, and not
just because it's the kind of place...

06:09.680 --> 06:11.671
where people still
smile at each other...

06:11.800 --> 06:15.156
- Bye.
- but because it hasn't changed much
in the past 25 years.

06:15.280 --> 06:19.159
And since I'm not a guy who's big on
change, this town fits me like a glove.

06:23.720 --> 06:26.029
I got Annie's ten-speed
all cleaned up and polished.

06:26.160 --> 06:29.072
New seats, new tyres.
I couldn't wait to show it to her.

06:32.960 --> 06:35.554
This is our house.
24 Maple Drive.

06:35.680 --> 06:38.069
Annie was just in grammar school
when we bought it.

06:38.200 --> 06:41.954
A few years later, we got
a surprise package-- our son Matt.

06:42.080 --> 06:44.674
I love this house.
I love that I taught my kids...

06:44.800 --> 06:46.677
to ride their bikes
in the driveway.

06:46.800 --> 06:49.394
I love that I slept with them
in tents in the backyard.

06:49.520 --> 06:53.035
I love that we carved our initials
in the tree out front.

06:53.160 --> 06:55.276
This house is warm in the winter,
cool in the summer...

06:55.400 --> 06:57.675
and looks spectacular
with Christmas lights.

06:57.800 --> 07:01.429
It's a great house,
and I never want to move.

07:01.560 --> 07:03.596
But the think I think
I like best about this house...

07:03.720 --> 07:06.280
are the voices I hear
when I walk through the door.

07:06.400 --> 07:08.675
- Hey. Hi. You got out early.
- Hi.

07:08.800 --> 07:10.995
- Where is she?
- Oh, she's, uh, unpacking.

07:11.120 --> 07:15.671
She looks-- She looks so fabulous,
just fabulous. Different.

07:15.800 --> 07:18.473
- Anyway, she can't wait to see you.
- Different.

07:18.600 --> 07:20.795
- Ciao, Papa.
- Hey.

07:20.920 --> 07:22.831
Annie brought me this candy bar
all the way from Rome.

07:22.960 --> 07:24.996
Let's not get it
on our American furniture.

07:25.120 --> 07:27.588
Matty. The high tops.

07:29.120 --> 07:33.159
- Hey, grazie.
- Hey, you're welcome.

07:33.280 --> 07:37.273
- What do you mean, different?
- Oh.

07:43.320 --> 07:46.630
- Annie.
- Hi, Dad.

07:47.280 --> 07:50.431
Hey, hey, hey!

07:50.560 --> 07:53.996
- God, I missed you.
- You look all lit up inside.

07:54.120 --> 07:56.918
Oh, I feel
all lit up inside.

07:57.040 --> 07:59.713
- Maybe we should go to Rome
for a few months, honey.
- Oh, you two would love it.

07:59.840 --> 08:02.434
It's the most romantic place
on Earth.

08:02.560 --> 08:05.916
- You smell pretty good too.
- Oh, you like it? It was a present.

08:06.040 --> 08:08.838
Doesn't she look incredible?
I almost didn't recognize her.

08:08.960 --> 08:12.839
Come on. Dinner's on the stove.
Honey, you wanna come?

08:12.960 --> 08:15.918
Oh, Mom, I had this pasta in Florence.
I forget what it's called.

08:21.200 --> 08:22.792
All right. Now that
we're all back under one roof...

08:22.920 --> 08:25.434
we have some very important items
to discuss.

08:25.560 --> 08:28.791
First on the list: Who wants to go
to the Laker game on Thursday?

08:28.920 --> 08:31.480
- Oh.
- Me. Definitely yes.

08:31.600 --> 08:32.919
Okay, and with
your busy schedule too.

08:33.039 --> 08:35.076
Honey, I can't. I have
inventory to do that night.

08:35.200 --> 08:38.351
- Aw.
- Uh, Thursday, sure. Absolutely.

08:38.480 --> 08:41.597
- Okay.
- Matty, could you use your fork?

08:41.720 --> 08:44.792
Number two: Paul Simon
is coming to the Forum...

08:44.920 --> 08:46.751
and I think I can
get us great seats.

08:46.880 --> 08:52.000
- Um, yeah, sure.
- All right. Paul Simon's
an "um, yeah, sure..."

08:52.120 --> 08:54.350
which I believe
translates to a yes?

08:54.480 --> 08:56.948
- All right. I'll call that guy.
- Um, honey?

08:57.080 --> 08:58.991
Could you please get that
bottle of wine in the fridge for me?

08:59.120 --> 09:02.112
- Sure.
- Dad, wait. Um, I don't know.

09:02.240 --> 09:05.915
- You don't want to see Paul Simon?
- No, l-l do. It's just, um--

09:06.040 --> 09:07.234
- Well, what is it?
- Well--

09:07.360 --> 09:09.590
- Honey, is something going on?
- Yes.

09:09.720 --> 09:13.838
Yeah, it is, Mom. Uh-- God, this is
a hard thing to tell parents.

09:13.960 --> 09:16.872
Especially when they're
my parents. Oh, God.

09:17.000 --> 09:18.672
Honey, just say it.
What's the big deal?

09:18.800 --> 09:21.075
- Yeah.
- Okay.

09:23.800 --> 09:27.873
I met somebody in Rome.
Um, he's an American.

09:28.000 --> 09:31.993
Uh, he's from L.A., actually,
and, um, his name's Bryan MacKenzie.

09:32.120 --> 09:35.954
And he's this
completely wonderful...

09:36.080 --> 09:39.755
wonderful, amazing man, and--

09:39.880 --> 09:42.553
Well, we, we started
seeing each other...

09:42.680 --> 09:45.797
a lot, and, um...

09:45.920 --> 09:47.797
we fell in love.

09:47.920 --> 09:50.639
It actually happened.
And, uh...

09:50.760 --> 09:55.959
we've decided to get married
which means that I'm engaged!

09:56.080 --> 09:58.958
I'm engaged!
I'm getting married!

10:01.040 --> 10:04.715
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

10:04.840 --> 10:06.910
Well, my, my.

10:07.040 --> 10:10.828
Oh, so-- Oh, my. And that's
your engagement ring, huh?

10:10.960 --> 10:14.396
Yes, yes! We got it
at a flea market outside of Rome.

10:14.520 --> 10:18.479
The guy we bought it from said
it was at least 100 years old.

10:18.600 --> 10:22.673
- Wow.
- So, Dad. Stop it. Say something.

10:25.280 --> 10:26.793
I-l'm sorry.
What did you say?

10:26.920 --> 10:29.718
Dad, I met a man in Rome,
and he's wonderful...

10:29.840 --> 10:33.037
and brilliant,
and we're getting married.

10:35.040 --> 10:37.554
- Mom, what's he doing?
- George.

10:38.720 --> 10:40.995
George, what is it?

10:43.360 --> 10:46.875
Well. This is-- This--

10:47.000 --> 10:49.195
This is ridiculous.

10:49.320 --> 10:51.834
- What?
- You're-- You're-- You're
too young to get married.

10:51.960 --> 10:54.952
Too young? Dad, I'm 22.
If I'm not mistaken...

10:55.080 --> 10:57.640
that's, that's a year older
than Mom was when you guys got married.

10:57.760 --> 11:00.877
- That is absolutely not true.
- Oh, no, you-- Ha!

11:01.000 --> 11:02.752
You're absolutely wrong.

11:02.880 --> 11:05.553
- You were this age when I married you?
- No! I was younger.

11:05.680 --> 11:08.911
I was this age
when she was born.

11:09.040 --> 11:11.315
That-- That-- That doesn't matter.
Times have changed.

11:11.440 --> 11:15.956
You mother was mature, and, uh,
22 isn't what it used to--

11:16.080 --> 11:19.675
Matty, would you turn on
the air conditioner? It's hot in here.

11:19.800 --> 11:21.870
I thought-- I thought you didn't
believe in marriage.

11:22.000 --> 11:24.468
I thought that it meant
that a woman lost her identity.

11:24.600 --> 11:26.989
I-l thought you wanted to get a job
before you settled down...

11:27.120 --> 11:29.236
so you could earn money
and be your own person.

11:29.360 --> 11:30.952
All right. Hold on.

11:31.080 --> 11:34.356
I didn't think I believed
in marriage until I met Bryan.

11:34.480 --> 11:36.436
And Bryan's not like any other guy
I've ever known.

11:36.560 --> 11:38.391
I want to be married to him.

11:38.520 --> 11:41.080
And I'm not gonna lose
my identity with him...

11:41.200 --> 11:44.636
because he's not
some overpowering, macho guy.

11:44.760 --> 11:48.719
I mean, he's like you, Dad,
except he's brilliant.

11:48.840 --> 11:52.037
He happens to love the fact
that I want to be an architect.

11:52.160 --> 11:55.197
He wants me to design
a house for us to live in.

11:55.320 --> 11:58.153
He said he'd move
anywhere I got a job.

11:58.280 --> 12:00.157
Give me a little credit, George.

12:00.280 --> 12:03.078
I'm not gonna marry some ape
who wants me to wear...

12:03.200 --> 12:05.350
go-go boots and an apron.

12:05.480 --> 12:09.075
I'm telling you you'll love him.
He's a genius.

12:09.200 --> 12:11.077
And sweet.

12:11.200 --> 12:16.035
And l-- I love him more
than anything in the world.

12:16.160 --> 12:18.754
- What does Bryan do?
- Who's Bryan?

12:21.400 --> 12:26.474
- I forgot his name!
- He's an independent
communications consultant.

12:26.600 --> 12:28.795
- Independent?
- Yes.

12:28.920 --> 12:33.311
Yeah. That's code for "unemployed." This
is perfect. You meet an unemployed...

12:33.440 --> 12:36.716
amazingly brilliant non-ape
that I'm going to have to support.

12:36.840 --> 12:39.434
I suppose I'm going to have to hire him
and fire some hard-working guy...

12:39.560 --> 12:41.915
with three kids
because my son-in-law--

12:42.040 --> 12:45.430
the, the independent
communications consultant--

12:45.560 --> 12:47.516
can't get a job anywhere else.

12:47.640 --> 12:51.030
No wonder he'll move
anywhere you get a job.

12:51.160 --> 12:53.958
You're not getting married,
and that's it, and that's final.

12:54.080 --> 12:57.436
And I don't like you calling me George.
I mean, when did this start?

12:57.560 --> 12:59.551
Daddy, what is wrong with you?

13:06.240 --> 13:08.276
What? You're telling me
you're happy about this ?

13:08.400 --> 13:10.356
George, please, will you stop
acting like a lunatic father...

13:10.480 --> 13:12.869
and go out and talk to her
before she runs out that door...

13:13.000 --> 13:15.070
marries this kid
and we never see her again?

13:19.040 --> 13:20.917
All right.

13:22.320 --> 13:25.471
"Kid." How do you know he's a kid?
He could be 45 years old.

13:41.720 --> 13:43.597
An independent
communications consultant...

13:43.720 --> 13:47.633
does not mean
he's an unemployable non-ape.

13:47.760 --> 13:51.150
Bryan happens to be
a computer genius.

13:51.280 --> 13:54.113
Companies send him all over the world
hooking up these complex systems.

13:54.240 --> 13:57.118
Major banks and corporations
send him to, to Tokyo...

13:57.240 --> 13:58.798
and Brazil and Geneva.

13:58.920 --> 14:00.558
I mean, he's--
He's a genius.

14:00.680 --> 14:04.593
You mentioned that.
How old is this genius?

14:04.720 --> 14:07.917
Twenty-six, not forty-five.

14:08.040 --> 14:10.873
You guys still think I can't hear you
when you're one room away.

14:14.800 --> 14:17.519
If you love him so much,
I know I'll love him too.

14:23.280 --> 14:26.238
- Bryan?
- Mackenzie.

14:26.360 --> 14:28.635
Bryan MacKenzie.

14:28.760 --> 14:30.876
- Yeah.
- I can't wait to meet him.

14:31.000 --> 14:34.072
Good, 'cause he'll be here
in an hour to meet you.

14:36.080 --> 14:38.514
I suppose you're not in the mood
for a little one-on-one?

14:38.640 --> 14:42.030
- Daddy, I'm wearing heels.
- Come to the right place.

14:47.960 --> 14:51.953
I've got sunshine

14:52.080 --> 14:54.196
On a cloudy day

14:57.200 --> 15:00.988
When it's cold outside

15:01.120 --> 15:03.588
I've got the month of May

15:05.520 --> 15:08.353
-He's got it behind the back. The crowd
is going wild. The crowd is going wild.
-I guess

15:08.480 --> 15:10.710
- It's-- It's--
- You say

15:10.840 --> 15:15.072
What can make me feel this way

15:15.200 --> 15:18.317
My girl, my girl
my girl

15:18.440 --> 15:21.591
- Talkin' 'bout my girl
- Hey!

15:21.720 --> 15:27.352
My girl, ooh-ooh

15:36.160 --> 15:38.435
Hey, hey, hey

15:40.640 --> 15:42.949
- Hey, hey, hey
- Yes.

15:45.600 --> 15:46.874
- Dad!
- Yes!

15:47.000 --> 15:49.594
Oh, travelling!

15:49.720 --> 15:53.508
I don't need no money

15:53.640 --> 15:56.950
Fortune or fame

15:58.440 --> 16:02.718
I got all the riches, baby

16:02.840 --> 16:05.274
- This is it. Eight up.
- One man can claim.

16:05.400 --> 16:06.594
- Go.
- Ready?

16:07.640 --> 16:10.200
Well, I guess

16:10.320 --> 16:12.436
- You'll say
- Hold on.
- No!

16:12.560 --> 16:16.997
- What can make me feel this way
- Hold on. Hold on. Hold on.
No, no, no, no. No!

16:17.120 --> 16:20.351
My girl, my girl
my girl

16:20.480 --> 16:23.119
- Talkin' 'bout my girl
- Yes!

16:23.240 --> 16:26.437
My girl
Talkin' 'bout my girl

16:26.560 --> 16:29.233
- I've got sunshine on a cloudy day
- All right.

16:29.360 --> 16:31.954
With my girl

16:32.080 --> 16:33.718
I've even got the month of May

16:33.840 --> 16:35.273
You're not really getting married,
are you?

16:35.400 --> 16:37.675
Dad, stop!

16:48.960 --> 16:51.679
- So can you see him?
What does he look like?
- He just drove up.

16:52.640 --> 16:55.473
And?

16:55.600 --> 16:58.114
He drove too fast.

17:09.880 --> 17:14.112
Well, wait. So, George,
you want to meet him?

17:14.240 --> 17:16.913
Do I want to meet him?

17:23.760 --> 17:27.195
- Oh, hello. Hi.
- Hello, I'm Brian MacKenzie.

17:27.319 --> 17:29.709
Good. I'm Nina Banks.

17:29.840 --> 17:31.910
Yes. Yes, I recognize you
from your picture.

17:32.040 --> 17:33.871
- Yes, come in, please.
- The one Annie had with her in Rome.

17:34.000 --> 17:38.835
- Yes. Oh, good. Come in.
- Okay. Hello, Mr Banks.

17:38.960 --> 17:41.952
It was the first time I ever
hated the sound of my own name.

17:42.080 --> 17:44.992
- Hi.
- I've heard so much about you.

17:45.120 --> 17:47.190
It's great
to finally meet you, sir.

17:47.320 --> 17:50.756
"Sir." Two words
now crossed my mind:

17:50.880 --> 17:52.677
"brown" and "nose."

17:52.800 --> 17:56.429
Annie talks about you so much,
I feel like I already know you.

17:56.560 --> 17:59.358
- Bryan.
- Oh, Annie.

18:08.720 --> 18:11.678
- So this is him.
- Oh, he's just-- Uh, just.

18:11.800 --> 18:14.837
A little nervous. Just like one
of those situations you read about...

18:14.960 --> 18:17.679
you know,
meeting the in-laws.

18:17.800 --> 18:21.395
But you two seem great. I'm sure
I have nothing to be nervous about.

18:21.520 --> 18:23.750
But, uh, still, l--

18:23.880 --> 18:26.155
Let's, let's, uh, uh,
go into the, uh, uh, the, uh--

18:26.280 --> 18:28.475
The-- uh-- Great.

18:28.600 --> 18:30.750
- I think he's adorable.
- I don't like him.

18:30.880 --> 18:34.190
- Oh, George, for God--
- He's wearing Nikes.

18:37.360 --> 18:39.874
- Mom, where's Matty?
- Oh, he fell asleep watching TV.

18:40.000 --> 18:43.470
- Oh, well, you'll meet him tomorrow.
- Okay.

18:43.600 --> 18:45.477
- Sit down.
- So.

18:45.600 --> 18:48.751
Um, how did you two, uh, meet?

18:48.880 --> 18:53.317
Oh. We were the only two people
at this revival house in Rome...

18:53.440 --> 18:56.273
for a midnight showing
of Bringing Up Baby.

18:56.400 --> 18:58.914
- We kept hearing each other laugh.
- And at all the same places.

18:59.040 --> 19:01.508
Yeah. When it was over,
I picked him up.

19:01.640 --> 19:03.437
Oh, no, no, no. I went over
to you to ask directions...

19:03.560 --> 19:06.757
and then one thing
led to another and--

19:06.880 --> 19:08.916
And that was it.
For the next three months...

19:09.040 --> 19:10.951
we never left
each other's sight.

19:11.080 --> 19:14.868
We went to all these museums,
all these great concerts, the opera.

19:15.000 --> 19:18.310
We travelled to the country. Remember
that place we stayed in Tuscany?

19:18.440 --> 19:21.113
Oh, with the, uh--

19:21.240 --> 19:24.038
- Uh, suffice it to say,
it was not a four-star hotel.
- No.

19:24.160 --> 19:26.071
You have a very brave daughter.

19:28.240 --> 19:31.073
Bryan, um, what is it exactly
that you do?

19:31.200 --> 19:33.714
Annie was saying
something about computers.

19:33.840 --> 19:36.957
Uh, yes, uh, I'm an independent
communications consultant.

19:37.080 --> 19:38.798
Yeah, yeah,
that part I heard.

19:38.920 --> 19:41.150
Sounds fake, right?
Like it's not a real job?

19:41.280 --> 19:43.555
- No, we wouldn't say that. No.
- That's what my dad said...

19:43.680 --> 19:45.272
when he first heard
what I was doing.

19:45.400 --> 19:48.517
But, um, what it is,
uh, in this case:

19:48.640 --> 19:50.437
Uh, Pacific lnternational Bank
sent me to Rome to hook up...

19:50.560 --> 19:52.869
the X-Dot connection
to their European subsidiary.

19:53.000 --> 19:57.630
Um-- Uh, all European computers, uh,
communicate on the Dot 25 network.

19:57.760 --> 19:59.910
And, uh, since Pacific lnternational
is an L.A.-based firm...

20:00.040 --> 20:04.113
they wanted to interface with standard
European protocol, so I set 'em up.

20:06.160 --> 20:10.073
And, uh, why are you, uh, independent?
What was that?

20:10.200 --> 20:13.237
Because no one can afford
to keep him on staff.

20:13.360 --> 20:17.319
Well, I guess that's true,
basically, but, uh--

20:17.440 --> 20:21.513
You know, driving down here,
I tried to put myself in your place.

20:21.640 --> 20:23.790
Your daughter comes home
after spending four months in Rome...

20:23.920 --> 20:26.275
a-and I'm sure you couldn't wait
to see her, and she shocks you...

20:26.400 --> 20:28.675
with the news
that she's getting married.

20:28.800 --> 20:30.756
And to somebody
you've never met before.

20:30.880 --> 20:33.269
I'm sure that
must've been pretty...

20:33.400 --> 20:36.358
um, heavy...

20:36.480 --> 20:39.392
to use a word
from your generation.

20:39.520 --> 20:42.193
I just wanna say
that I'm an upstanding citizen.

20:42.320 --> 20:44.197
I've-l've never been
engaged before.

20:44.320 --> 20:47.915
I've, uh, never really
been in love before.

20:48.040 --> 20:52.272
And, uh, I think Annie's
the greatest person I've ever met.

20:52.400 --> 20:54.834
And I can't wait
to marry her and...

20:54.960 --> 20:58.316
one day have children
and grandchildren.

21:01.120 --> 21:05.238
And I'm gonna do my best
to be supportive of her dreams.
And she's a very gifted architect.

21:05.360 --> 21:08.432
Um-- I'm just thrilled
that I met her.

21:11.720 --> 21:13.597
I love your daughter.

21:13.720 --> 21:18.430
And the feelings that I have for her
are never gonna change.

21:18.560 --> 21:21.711
And I'm here to stay.

21:21.840 --> 21:24.274
- Oh, honey.
- Mom.

21:28.280 --> 21:30.157
I'm so happy for you.

21:30.280 --> 21:32.316
That's okay, Mr Banks,
We don't have to hug.

21:32.440 --> 21:34.749
- Well, uh, maybe later.
- I know.

21:34.880 --> 21:39.158
Well, that was just, um--
That was just the best thing
I've ever heard anybody say.

21:40.800 --> 21:42.995
- Oh. Good.
- Well, I meant it.

21:43.120 --> 21:45.395
Listen, I want to take Bryan out
for a drive, show him around San Marino.

21:45.520 --> 21:47.795
- Okay, honey. Good.
- Annie, it's a little nippy out.

21:47.920 --> 21:50.115
- You might want to put on a sweater.
- Oh, Dad, it's okay. I'm kinda warm.

21:50.240 --> 21:51.753
Still, there's a chill in the air,
and you've been on a plane.

21:51.880 --> 21:54.075
- Dad, I'm fine.
- Annie, it is kinda cold out.

21:54.200 --> 21:55.155
- It is?
- Yeah.

21:55.280 --> 21:58.750
- All right, thanks. I'll get my jacket.
- All right.

21:58.880 --> 22:02.759
Right then, I realized
my day had passed.

22:02.880 --> 22:06.156
She'll always love me, of course,
but not in the same way.

22:06.280 --> 22:09.192
I was no longer the man
in my little girl's life.

22:09.320 --> 22:11.754
I was like an old shoe,
the kind we manufacture...

22:11.880 --> 22:15.873
and get all excited about and then
after a few years discontinue.

22:16.000 --> 22:20.152
That was me now:
Mr Discontinued.

22:20.280 --> 22:22.919
Mom? Don't wait up, okay?
We might stop for a cappuccino.

22:23.040 --> 22:25.235
Oh, okay, fine.
Well, good night, Bryan.

22:25.360 --> 22:27.476
Good night.
Um, good night, Mr Banks.

22:27.600 --> 22:29.750
Oh, you can call him George,
or Dad.

22:29.880 --> 22:32.394
- George will be fine.
- Okay. Uh--

22:32.520 --> 22:34.875
I'll say it next time I see you.

22:35.000 --> 22:38.754
Drive carefully, and don't forget
to fasten your condom.

22:38.880 --> 22:40.552
- Dad!
- Seat belt!

22:40.680 --> 22:43.399
I meant-- I meant
seat belt.

22:43.520 --> 22:47.752
Um, I'm putting your father to bed.
This has been a very big night for him.

22:47.880 --> 22:49.552
- Bye.
- Okay.
- Well, good night.

22:49.680 --> 22:50.999
- Have fun.
- Bye.
- Good night.

22:51.120 --> 22:53.714
- Bye.
- Bye-bye. Have fun.
- Bye.

22:56.320 --> 22:58.788
This is a great kid.

22:58.920 --> 23:01.434
- It'll never last.
- Wanna bet?

23:01.560 --> 23:03.835
Nina, Annie's much too spirited
for this kid.

23:03.960 --> 23:07.316
He's totally wrong for her.
I give it two months, tops. One month.

23:07.440 --> 23:10.238
This is the right guy for Annie, George.
I'm telling you, I feel it in my bones.

23:10.360 --> 23:12.396
- I mean, we're two lucky parents.
We are.
- Lucky? Oh!

23:12.520 --> 23:15.398
What about his laugh? It was such
a giveaway. It was so phoney with his--

23:16.520 --> 23:18.511
- I thought it was totally sincere.
- Oh, please.

23:18.640 --> 23:21.313
What about that little rehearsed speech
he gave? It was right out of a book.

23:21.440 --> 23:23.351
How To Grease Your Future
Mother-ln-Law.

23:23.480 --> 23:26.790
You're off here, George,
really. I thought it was
completely from his heart.

23:26.920 --> 23:29.036
- Why do you think I cried?
- Good question.

23:29.160 --> 23:31.515
I don't know why either of you cried.
I'm losing my voice.

23:31.640 --> 23:34.632
- Are my glands swollen or something?
- Let me see. No. No, honey, no.

23:34.760 --> 23:36.512
And what about
the way he kept touching her?

23:36.640 --> 23:38.915
- What do you mean?
- What do you mean what do I mean?

23:39.040 --> 23:41.110
- He could-- He couldn't
keep his hands off her.
- Oh, yes. Kind of like...

23:41.240 --> 23:44.630
when we were engaged, except that
wasn't all you couldn't keep off me.

23:44.760 --> 23:47.718
That was different.
And we certainly never
acted that way in your parents' house.

23:47.840 --> 23:51.230
Ah! You want me to name all the rooms
we did it in at my parents' house?

23:51.360 --> 23:53.920
That was different.
We were like two imbeciles.

23:54.040 --> 23:56.634
- This is our child we're talking about.
- Our child? Oh, George.

23:56.760 --> 24:00.594
You know, I still think you see Annie
as a seven-year-old in pigtails.

24:00.720 --> 24:02.358
Well, you know, that just shows
how much you know about me...

24:02.480 --> 24:04.835
because that is not at all
how I see her.

24:04.960 --> 24:07.554
Right, a seven-year-old
with pigtails.

24:07.680 --> 24:10.513
I mean, here's the thing: We have
no idea who this Bryan really is.

24:10.640 --> 24:13.359
- Oh. Uh-huh.
- I mean, if that's his real name.
I mean, who knows?

24:13.480 --> 24:16.836
You know, maybe he already has a wife.
You read about these cases every day--

24:16.960 --> 24:20.635
you know, men who have wives and
families stashed all across the country.

24:20.760 --> 24:23.672
I mean, he could be a professional
con artist who meets innocents abroad...

24:23.800 --> 24:28.351
and gives them this song and dance about
being an independent whatever that was.

24:28.480 --> 24:31.438
And then skips out after bilking them
for all they're worth.

24:31.560 --> 24:34.199
- Wh-What are you doing?
- I'm getting ready for bed.

24:34.320 --> 24:37.073
You know, then I suppose you're not
interested that I believe
I remember seeing someone...

24:37.200 --> 24:39.634
who looked like Bryan's twin
on America's Most Wanted.

24:39.760 --> 24:42.877
You're right.
I'm not.

24:43.000 --> 24:45.195
George.

24:45.320 --> 24:47.197
George, l-l thought he was great.

24:47.320 --> 24:49.595
I liked him a lot.
And I'm really ha-- Ann--

24:49.720 --> 24:53.190
George, will you please stop making
that face? I'm very happy for Annie.

24:53.320 --> 24:55.754
I'm excited for her.
This is a big deal.

24:55.880 --> 24:59.395
I think that we should
at least hug.

24:59.520 --> 25:02.034
This is great news.

25:02.160 --> 25:04.037
Oh, a wedding.

25:06.360 --> 25:09.352
Father of the bride.
Can you believe it?

25:19.000 --> 25:21.275
Forty-eight hours later,
the wedding was still on...

25:21.400 --> 25:24.597
and we were on our way to Bel-Air
to meet Bryan's folks.

25:24.720 --> 25:26.995
I don't know why we have to have
brunch with total strangers.

25:27.120 --> 25:31.159
Because their son is marrying
our daughter and it's not
an unusual custom meeting the in-laws.

25:31.280 --> 25:34.556
You know, that's another thing.
I hate that expression: in-laws.

25:34.680 --> 25:37.990
What does it mean anyway?
We're legally bound to these people?

25:38.120 --> 25:42.033
I don't wanna be "in-lawed," especially
to people who live in Bel-Air.

25:42.160 --> 25:45.675
I mean, what kind of people
have brunch and live in Bel-Air?

25:45.800 --> 25:48.109
Rich people.

25:48.240 --> 25:52.279
They probably live in the one shack
in the middle of all these mansions.

25:52.400 --> 25:55.198
- Nice mood, George.
- What? I'm in a good mood.

25:59.600 --> 26:02.512
Okay, I think this is it.
Yeah.

26:05.200 --> 26:08.158
- Nice shack, babe.
- Worse. It's the biggest house
on the street.

26:08.280 --> 26:11.750
Now we're related to
pretentious snobs. Just what we need.

26:34.600 --> 26:37.034
You look very handsome, George,
way too young to be in-lawed.

26:37.160 --> 26:40.789
Well, it really shouldn't matter
how I look. We're not here
to win their approval.

26:42.680 --> 26:44.398
Just because you
changed your outfit five times.

26:44.520 --> 26:46.351
Oh, and you didn't try on
nine different shirts?

26:46.480 --> 26:47.754
- Two.
- Two.

26:47.880 --> 26:49.518
Two long-sleeve,
two short-sleeve.

26:49.640 --> 26:53.030
- Hi!
- George, Nina, welcome.

26:53.160 --> 26:54.479
- Hi, nice to meet you.
- I'm John.

26:54.600 --> 26:57.717
- How do you do?
- Hi, I'm Joanna.

26:57.840 --> 26:59.159
- Welcome. Come in, please.
- Welcome to our house. Come on in.

26:59.280 --> 27:02.113
- Come in.
- Thank you so much. Well.

27:02.240 --> 27:05.869
All I could think about
was the size of this place.

27:06.000 --> 27:08.389
We could've parked our whole house
in the foyer.

27:08.520 --> 27:12.069
Ah, what a nerve-racking thing,
meeting your future in-laws.

27:12.200 --> 27:14.270
- Yeah.
- What a relief. You two
look perfectly normal.

27:14.400 --> 27:17.915
Oh, well, I am.

27:18.040 --> 27:20.759
I have to tell you,
we got so nervous about today...

27:20.880 --> 27:24.429
about meeting the two of you,
l-l must've tried
on three different outfits.

27:24.560 --> 27:27.393
- Oh.
- I changed my shirt four times.

27:27.520 --> 27:31.991
- Can you imagine anyone
being that jerky?
- Oh, I know.

27:32.120 --> 27:33.951
So, come on in. I thought
we'd have lunch in here.

27:34.080 --> 27:36.469
- Oh, what a great room.
- Marta.
- Thank you, Marta.

27:36.600 --> 27:41.071
Marta, estos son nuestros in-laws,
George and Nina Banks.

27:41.200 --> 27:43.077
- Hello.
- How do you do? Hi.

27:43.200 --> 27:46.715
Oh, and here's
the rest of our family.

27:46.840 --> 27:50.594
Oh, don't worry. They look like killers,
but they're actually quite friendly.

27:50.720 --> 27:53.518
As long as you're relaxed,
why, they're relaxed.

27:53.640 --> 27:56.438
Hi, puppy, puppy, puppy.
Why, you're--

27:56.560 --> 27:59.552
All right, fellas, that's enough.
Go on. Release! Good boys.

27:59.680 --> 28:01.511
- Well, why don't we all sit down.
- Please.

28:01.640 --> 28:03.676
- Oh, thank you.
- All right. Here we go.

28:03.800 --> 28:06.917
- George. Honey.
- Thank you, sweetheart.

28:07.040 --> 28:09.634
I don't know if the kids told you, but
we were over in Europe on business...

28:09.760 --> 28:11.990
and we stopped in Rome
to see Bryan.

28:12.120 --> 28:15.430
So we got to spend a few days
with Annie. Oh, boy!

28:15.560 --> 28:18.632
- We just fell in love
with her immediately.
- Isn't she great?

28:18.760 --> 28:20.830
Yes. We just couldn't
be happier about this.

28:20.960 --> 28:23.599
How did you, uh,
take the news, George?

28:23.720 --> 28:25.597
Me?

28:25.720 --> 28:29.633
Uh, truthfully, uh, I was
a little surprised.

28:29.760 --> 28:32.752
- I was shocked.
- So was l.

28:32.880 --> 28:35.314
After all, they'd only known each other
a few months.

28:35.440 --> 28:37.908
Exactly. And Annie's
just finishing up school.

28:38.040 --> 28:40.110
Absolutely. Oh, believe me,
I tossed and turned over this one...

28:40.240 --> 28:43.073
but the bottom line
is they're in love.

28:43.200 --> 28:45.839
They're over 21, and whether they're
rushing into this or not...

28:45.960 --> 28:48.110
may be not for us to say.

28:48.240 --> 28:51.755
Right. "Not for us to say."
We're only their parents.

28:51.880 --> 28:54.838
I was about to say these very words
out loud when he hit me with--

28:54.960 --> 28:57.713
Yeah, sooner or later,
you just have to let your kids go...

28:57.840 --> 28:59.717
and hope you
brought 'em up right.

29:02.760 --> 29:06.275
George. Nina. Darling.

29:06.400 --> 29:08.436
This guy was making
a little too much sense for me.

29:08.560 --> 29:12.314
Suddenly my shirt collar felt like
it was starting to strangle me.

29:12.440 --> 29:14.476
To George and Nina...

29:14.600 --> 29:16.909
and a future
of wonderful memories.

29:17.040 --> 29:19.156
First, the wedding
of our children...

29:19.280 --> 29:22.317
and the happiness we'll share
watching their lives.

29:22.440 --> 29:25.830
Then sharing the joy
of our grandchildren together.

29:27.000 --> 29:30.675
Birthday parties,
graduation--

29:36.920 --> 29:40.708
Now I knew where they got the
expression "like father, like son."

29:40.840 --> 29:44.116
- I also knew I needed some air.
- Can you tell me where the restroom is?

29:44.240 --> 29:47.789
Oh, actually, the one down here
is a mess. We're remodelling.

29:47.920 --> 29:51.754
Uh, why don't you try
the one at the top of the stairs?
It's the seventh door on the left.

29:51.880 --> 29:53.552
- Second?
- Seventh.

29:53.680 --> 29:56.797
- Seventh.
- Seventh.

31:15.760 --> 31:19.150
I'm leaving.
I'm relaxed, and I'm leaving.

31:40.760 --> 31:42.318
Relent.

31:42.440 --> 31:44.670
Re-- Recoil.

31:44.800 --> 31:46.313
Reverse.

31:49.280 --> 31:52.590
- Well, I hope George hasn't
gotten lost up there.
- Oh, no, he's gonna be fine.

31:52.720 --> 31:55.280
Okay.

31:55.400 --> 31:59.075
Well, um--
Such a lovely sculpture.

31:59.200 --> 32:01.873
Oh. Doesn't it have a wonderful
sense of motion?

32:02.000 --> 32:05.436
We got it in Denmark. All the-- Quite
a lot of my family's from Copenhagen.

32:05.560 --> 32:09.189
- Is that right?
- Oh, yeah. Doesn't it have
a wonderful sense of balance?

32:09.320 --> 32:11.311
- Oh, it's amazing.
- I was going to put it in the garden.

32:16.480 --> 32:19.199
Well, actually, uh, uh, Bryan spent
quite a few summers in Denmark.

32:19.320 --> 32:22.551
Uh, he now speaks
better Danish than, than Joanna.

32:24.200 --> 32:25.952
N-- Is that a fact?

32:37.200 --> 32:39.236
And we're planning a trip
back this summer.

32:39.360 --> 32:41.237
I think this is
a very beautiful spread here.

32:41.360 --> 32:44.397
- Oh, thank you.
- Well, shall--
should we wait for George?

33:10.240 --> 33:13.437
- Maybe I should, uh, check on George.
- No.

33:30.320 --> 33:34.711
- Release!
- Oh, man.

33:38.280 --> 33:42.193
Wow. No kidding?
Really? It went great?

33:42.320 --> 33:45.949
Uh, better than great. I mean, it, just,
just couldn't have gone better.

33:46.080 --> 33:48.036
God, I'm so relieved.

33:48.160 --> 33:51.277
I mean, who knows what can happen
at these things, you know?

33:51.400 --> 33:54.039
- This is great.
- Now I feel like the wedding's
officially on.

33:54.160 --> 33:56.037
Um, Dad, that looks so good.
This looks great.

33:56.160 --> 33:59.914
Um, Bryan's mom called with the names
of her immediate family.

34:05.360 --> 34:08.112
- Is this a joke?
- Not only is it not a joke...

34:08.239 --> 34:10.389
but eight of them are
from Copenhagen and well...

34:10.520 --> 34:13.114
it's the bride's family's
responsibility to--

34:13.239 --> 34:15.833
Do you have any idea what
a round-trip ticket from Denmark costs?

34:15.960 --> 34:17.951
Try eight round-trip tickets.

34:18.080 --> 34:19.956
Well, actually, it's nine.

34:20.080 --> 34:22.389
You see, Joanna's,
uh, cousin Gitte...

34:22.520 --> 34:27.310
is apparently a rather large woman
so she needs two seats.

34:27.440 --> 34:30.193
She can lop over into the aisle for all
I care 'cause there's no way I'm pay--

34:30.320 --> 34:31.594
Hi, everyone.
Sorry I'm late.

34:31.719 --> 34:33.472
- Hi.
- That's okay.
- How're you doing? Hi.

34:33.600 --> 34:35.397
- Hello.
- Hey, dude.
- Hi.

34:35.520 --> 34:38.273
- Oh. Here you are.
- Oh. Well, thank you.

34:39.800 --> 34:43.156
- It's "you're welcome" in Danish.
- Ah, thanks.

34:43.280 --> 34:47.159
This looks great. I hear you're
a whiz at the barbecue, Dad.

34:50.159 --> 34:54.676
Well. So have you two given any thought
to what kind of wedding you want?

34:54.800 --> 34:58.031
- Well, we've talked about it.
- Yes, and what do you think?

34:58.160 --> 34:59.718
Big? Small? Or--

34:59.840 --> 35:02.070
Well, it can't be too big.
We don't have that many friends.

35:02.200 --> 35:04.430
So we're talking
in the small vicinity, then?

35:04.560 --> 35:07.074
Well, no, she didn't say "small."
She said not too big.

35:07.200 --> 35:09.668
Yeah, but nothing fancy
or overblown, right?

35:09.800 --> 35:11.438
- Right.
- Right.

35:11.560 --> 35:14.358
So kind of the "less is more"
theory, huh, Annie?

35:14.480 --> 35:18.268
- Basically.
- The reason I'm asking all these
questions is I have a great idea...

35:18.400 --> 35:23.235
where we can have this lovely,
not small but not too big wedding.

35:23.360 --> 35:25.920
You do? Where?

35:26.040 --> 35:29.191
At our favourite restaurant, the place
we've been eating at for 15 years.

35:29.320 --> 35:33.757
The best.
The Steak Pit.

35:33.880 --> 35:37.429
- Dad, get serious.
- I don't think
you want the word "pit"...

35:37.560 --> 35:40.028
on a wedding invitation,
George.

35:40.160 --> 35:42.879
Really, Dad, a rib joint
with sawdust on the floor...

35:43.000 --> 35:45.389
isn't exactly what I had in mind
for my wedding.

35:45.520 --> 35:47.078
- No offence.
- Well, excuse me.

35:47.200 --> 35:49.156
What did you have in mind,
the Beverly Hills Hotel?

35:49.280 --> 35:52.317
No. Actually, what I'd like
is to have...

35:52.440 --> 35:54.670
my wedding in a church
and have the reception here.

35:54.800 --> 35:56.392
- Oh.
- That's what I was hoping for.

35:56.520 --> 35:58.397
Here?

36:05.600 --> 36:08.717
Don't I have
the greatest Dad in the world?

36:08.840 --> 36:11.070
- Hi.
- Hi.
- Hi.

36:11.200 --> 36:14.636
- Can we have some burgers?
- Okay, here's the bride burger
and your groom burger.

36:14.760 --> 36:17.638
And, uh, enjoy 'em. Now, go on
over there and see the jugglers.

36:17.760 --> 36:20.274
My dream wedding,
a barbecue wedding.

36:27.880 --> 36:29.950
- This is a better idea
than the Steak Pit.
- Yeah.

36:30.080 --> 36:33.516
We'll get some, uh, picnic tables
and, uh, crepe paper and balloons.

36:33.640 --> 36:38.031
You know, invite all our best pals.
I'll make my famous guacamole.

36:38.160 --> 36:41.516
A wedding at home.
This is a great idea.

